Hard Rock Hotel and Casino in Atlantic City Social Media Analysis¶

Nicholas Branco¶

This is the second part of my analysis of Hard Rock Hotel and Casino's social media analysis.

The Journey so Far¶

I began working at Hard Rock Hotel and Casino in Atlantic City on April 23, 2018 while working on my Master's degree in Data Science and Strategical analytics at Stockton University. I completed my semester with a project on a social media analysis of a network on Twitter focusing on anorexia. This got me thinking of my workplace's social media activity.

I found the Twitter page for Hard Rock...and it did not seem to be too active, suprisingly. I thought for sure that they would want to be druming up the hype for the new opening (the Atlantic City property was set to open on June 28, 2018), but it seemed like they didn't even care. I chalked this up to being too far from opening, though not much changed when I checked again a couple of weeks later.

Thus, I decided to look at the network over a few weeks, from before opening until after. This process is detailed in the R Notebook I have, though I will summarize here. I used Rtweet to collect data on Hard Rock's Twitter data nine times over a period of a month and a half. I tried to provide enough overlap so as to not miss any tweets. I then combined all of these datasets into one (well, two) and forced them to be unique. All of this was done in R, so now I want to finish the project in python.

Reading in the Data¶

Like in R, I will be using feather to transfer the data.

This is the first time I am using feather, and I have to say that it is very useful! It also has the capability to take a dataframe from Python and put it into R. I look forward to experimenting with it more and seeing what else it can do.

Analysis of the Data¶

Now that the data is in, I can begin to analyze it.

A Simple Graph¶

The first thing I want to take a look at is the tweets over time. I want to make a graph that shows how often tweets were posted monthly.

That's better. A simple count function will do to make this graph.

In [55]:
dates_posted = list(set(dates))
dates_posted = sorted(dates_posted, key=lambda d: tuple(map(int, d.split('-'))))

number_of_posts = []
new_dates = []
for date in dates_posted:
    y = dates.count(date)
    number_of_posts.append(y)
    date = date[6:]
    new_dates.append(date)
    
dates_posted = new_dates
    
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt; plt.rcdefaults()
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
 
y_pos = np.arange(len(dates_posted))

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(30,10))
plt.plot(dates_posted, number_of_posts)
plt.xticks(y_pos, dates_posted)
plt.ylabel('Number of Posts')
plt.title('Number of Twitter Posts per Day')

ax.spines['top'].set_visible(False)
ax.spines['right'].set_visible(False)
ax.spines['bottom'].set_visible(False)
ax.spines['left'].set_visible(False)

plt.savefig("yay.png")

plt.show()

A great start. It seemslike there are small spikes here and there when the weekends are, but then on 6/22 the amount of activity spiked. The Hard Rock AC friends and family opening was the next day, so this is pretty much what I expected. There is another large spike around 6/28 which was the official opening day.

I will provide more on this in an analysis section.

Who is Tweeting about Hard Rock?¶

Now, the idea is to go through the user data and see what I can find out. Let's take a look at what kind of people are tweeting about Hard Rock.

Much like the previous section, I will be using a count function to measure how many times each user is tweeting. This isn't quite a study of the "user data," but it will certainly tie into the later analysis.

Well, that did't work out to be as useful as I initially thought. However, we can use the code for something else: finding common words in the users' Twitter bios.

In [73]:
en_users = users[users.account_lang == 'en']

desc = []
for bio in en_users.description:
    wordlist = re.sub("[^\w]", " ",  bio).split()
    for word in wordlist:
        word = word.lower()
        desc.append(word)

bio = list(set(desc))

number = []
for word in bio:
    y = desc.count(word)
    number.append(y)
    
language = pd.DataFrame({'word' : bio,
 'number' : number,
  }, columns=['word', 'number'])


common_words = [
    'and', 
    'but', 
    'a', 
    'me', 
    'my', 
    'it', 
    'for', 
    'you', 
    'be', 
    'so', 
    'to',

    'https',
    'in',
    'co',
    't',
    'on'
    's',
    'we',
    'm'
]

for x in common_words:
    language = language[language.word.str.contains(x) == False]
    
language = language.sort_values(by=['number'],ascending=False)

Finally, the last part of this code is much like the first: a look at tweets over time, only now we will only look at Hard Rock AC.

In [80]:
tweets = feather.read_dataframe( "tweets" )

hardrock = tweets[tweets.screen_name == 'HardRockHCAC']

times = hardrock["created_at"]

dates = []

for post in times:
    post = str(post)
    dates.append(post[:post.find(" ")])
dates

dates_posted = list(set(dates))
dates_posted = sorted(dates_posted, key=lambda d: tuple(map(int, d.split('-'))))

number_of_posts = []
new_dates = []
for date in dates_posted:
    y = dates.count(date)
    number_of_posts.append(y)
    date = date[6:]
    new_dates.append(date)
    
dates_posted = new_dates
    
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt; plt.rcdefaults()
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
 
y_pos = np.arange(len(dates_posted))

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(30,10))
plt.plot(dates_posted, number_of_posts)
plt.xticks(y_pos, dates_posted)
plt.ylabel('Number of Posts')
plt.title('Number of Twitter Posts per Day')

ax.spines['top'].set_visible(False)
ax.spines['right'].set_visible(False)
ax.spines['bottom'].set_visible(False)
ax.spines['left'].set_visible(False)

plt.savefig("hard_rock_posts.png")

plt.show()
